04579nam a22006255i 9780300160642DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20181990ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001606427 a10.12987/97803001606422doi  a(DE-B1597)486779  a(OCoLC)1024019034  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aHV8964.S65bK48 2004eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a365/.45/09470904322204aThe History of the Gulag :bFrom Collectivization to the Great Terror /ced. by Grigory Sevostianov, Mary Habeck, Ronald Radosh. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2018] 4c©1990  a1 online resource (464 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tList Of Abbreviations -- tMap Of Gulag Sites, 1929–1941 -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Origins Of The Stalinist Gulag -- tChapter 2. Famine -- tChapter 3. Stabilization Of The System -- tChapter 4. The Great Terror -- tChapter 5. Beria’s “Reforms” -- tChapter 6. Mobilization And Repression -- tChapter 7. The Victims -- tConclusion: The Price Of Terror -- tBrief Biographies -- tList Of Selected Camps And Projects Of The OGPU-NKVD -- tExcerpts From The Criminal Codes Of The RSFSR And The Constitution Of The USSR -- tNotes -- tIndex Of Documents -- tGeneral Index -- tBooks In The Annals Of Communism Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe human cost of the Gulag, the Soviet labor camp system in which millions of people were imprisoned between 1920 and 1956, was staggering. Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn and others after him have written movingly about the Gulag, yet never has there been a thorough historical study of this unique and tragic episode in Soviet history. This groundbreaking book presents the first comprehensive, historically accurate account of the camp system. Russian historian Oleg Khlevniuk has mined the contents of extensive archives, including long-suppressed state and Communist Party documents, to uncover the secrets of the Gulag and how it became a central component of Soviet ideology and social policy.Khlevniuk argues persuasively that the Stalinist penal camps created in the 1930s were essentially different from previous camps. He shows that political motivations and paranoia about potential enemies contributed no more to the expansion of the Gulag than the economic incentive of slave labor did. And he offers powerful evidence that the Great Terror was planned centrally and targeted against particular categories of the population. Khlevniuk makes a signal contribution to Soviet history with this exceptionally informed and balanced view of the Gulag.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aConcentration campszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aForced laborzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aInternment campszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aPolitical prisonerszSoviet Union. 0aPrisonszSoviet UnionxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aConquest, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHabeck, Mary, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRadosh, Ronald, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSevostianov, Grigory, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831105380140 cprintz978030009284440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030016064240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300160642423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300160642/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY